sentence: The government shutdown is yesterday's news, and stocks are now in wait and see mode this morning as the market digests earnings from companies like Netflix (NFLX), Procter & Gamble (PG), Verizon (VZ), among others.
And even tariffs announced after the close haven't given the market a boost.
S&P 500 futures have dipped 0.1% at 8:28 a.m. this morning, while Dow Jones Industrial Average futures are little changed.
Nasdaq Composite futures have ticked up 0.1%.
Stocks may not be moving, but that doesn't make this a dull morning.
Oil is rallying, with WTI crude futures, the U.S. benchmark up 0.8% at $64.09 a barrel, while the 10-year Treasury yield has pulled back from three-year highs to 2.62% this morning.

The dollar is little changed against the euro, but is had fallen 0.5% to 110.37 yen even after the Bank of Japan's Haruhiko Kuroda said that the central bank wouldn't ending its extraordinary monetary policy any time soon, sending Japan's Nikkei up 1.3%.

-- Ben Levisohn

Shares of Netflix (NFLX) have risen more than 11% in early trading on Monday, after the company reported fourth-quarter earnings that showed better-than-expected subscriber additions.
Netflix's earnings per share of 41 cents met analysts' expectations, while revenue of $3.29 billion edged ahead of consensus.

But investors were most encouraged by the company's 8.33 million new subscribers--1.98 million domestic streaming subscriber net additions, and 6.36 million international, which surpassed the Street's high expectations.
Procter & Gamble (PG) has fallen 1.5% after it reported fiscal second-quarter earnings.
The home and personal products giant said it earned $1.19 a share, a nickel better than analysts expected.
Revenues rose 3.2% year over year to $17.39 billion, which matched consensus estimates.
However it's guidance didn't wow investors, as P&G expects earnings up 5% to 8%, to $4.12 to $4.23, compared to the $4.17 consensus.
with revenues up 3% to $67 billion, compared to the $67.12 consensus.
It also maintained its guidance for organic sales growth in the range of 2 % to 3% for fiscal 2018.
Verizon Communications (VZ) is up 3.4% this morning, following its mixed fourth-quarter earnings report and better-than-expected guidance.
Verizon said it earned 86 cents a share on revenue that rose 2.2% to $33.95 billion.
Analysts were looking for earnings per share of 88 cents on revenue of $33.2 billion.
For the full year, Verizon expects consolidated revenues will grow at a low-single digit percentage rate, above the consensus expectations of 1%.
Kimberly Clark (KMB) is climbing 1.5%, despite a downbeat fourth-quarter and mixed guidance.
Kimberly Clark said it earned $1.57 a share, on revenue that rose 9.8% year over year to $4.58 billion.
Analysts were looking for earnings of $1.54 on revenue of $4.61 billion.
Its guidance was mixed as it expects earnings between $6.90 and $7.20, on revenue of $18.44 billion to $18.62 billion.
Analysts are looking for earnings of $6.63 on revenue of $18.65 billion.
Adobe Systems (ADBE) is up 2.2% after its upbeat preannouncement.
It sees full-year earnings of $6.20, on revenue $8.7 billion, both metrics above consensus, and it got several analyst price target raises.
Tesla (TSLA) is 2.7% higher after it announced a new performance-based compensation package for CEO Elon Musk, with market cap and operational milestones.
For the next decade, Musk's award will vest based on whether or not he can meet metrics that include a $650 billion market cap, as well as revenue and profitability goals.
The award consists of a 10-year grant of stock options that vest in 12 tranches, each of which vests only if a pair of milestones are both met.
GoPro (GPRO) has dropped 6% after Morgan Stanley cut it to Underweight from Equal Weight.
The stock has had a rough start to the year, slashing its Q4 outlook and it's considering selling itself.

-- Teresa Rivas

Tariffs on solar panels got most of the attention after the close yesterday, but those aren't the only ones that the Trump administration is putting in place.
It also slapped stiff penalties on washing machines, at least the big ones used in American homes.
Companies be forced to pay a 20% tariff on the first 1.2 million washers, and then a 50% fee on anything above that.
No surprise, then, that shares of Whirlpool (WHR) have gained 5.4% to $175.56 at 9:15 a.m. this morning, as the company has been practically begging for these tariffs.
While the news is certainly good, it might not be quite as good as the market reaction suggests.
KeyBanc analyst Kenneth Zener said as much in a note released last night, calling the tariffs "good" but "not a panacea."
The reason: "Anticipating the tariffs, we estimate four+ months of LRW have been imported," Zener says.
Still, he remains optimistic that Whirlpool is headed for a turnaround--Zener reiterated his Outperform rating and $200 target.
Wither iPhone X?
A smartphone that didn't live up to the hype or an endangered species?
Apple (AAPL) faces those sobering questions after two analyst reports on Monday.

The shocker came late in the day: A research note from influential KGI Securities--as reported by news site Apple Insider--that initial shipments of the $1,000 phone were a disappointing 18 million in the fourth quarter.
That prompted Apple analyst Ming-Chi Kuo to speculate the dearth of demand for iPhone X could mean the "end of life" this year.
Apple has never discontinued an iPhone before unveiling a new model, usually in September.
Apple was not immediately available for comment.
Some consumers have shied from iPhone X - opting instead for the more-affordable iPhone 8 Plus and iPhone 8 since all three models were unveiled on Sept. 12.

"After the first wave of demand has been fulfilled, the market now worries that the high price of the iPhone X may weaken demand in the first quarter" of 2018, Sinolink Securities analyst Zhang Bin told Bloomberg in December.

Shares of Apple were already in retreat Monday, dipping 0.82% to $177, after Atlantic Equities James Cordwell cut his rating on the stock to Neutral from Overweight over concerns iPhone X demand is "starting to soften."
Indeed, murmurs of lower-than-expected sales of Apple's next-generation iPhone have percolated for weeks.
In late December, a Taiwanese paper, The Economic Times, and two boutique brokerage firms, Sinolink and JL Warren Capital, came to the same conclusion.

-- Jon Swartz
